		<td><b>Low-cost living room emulation machine</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />For ROM hack players worried about the <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?p=130249#p130249" class="postlink">Retron 5's drawbacks</a>, what living room emulation machine is better? Raspberry Pi?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>rainwarrior</b> [ Thu Jun 26, 2014 6:01 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: My Retron 5 arrived today!</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />There are a billion different computers available now that you could use for &quot;living room&quot; emulation, and I'd venture that most of them are better than a Retron 5 for playing homebrew and romhacks. HDMI output is easy to get nowadays, and there are plenty of low-cost media-centre oriented computers on the market for this kind of thing already.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Thu Jun 26, 2014 6:57 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Low-cost living room emulation machine</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />A PC made for the living room would have to overcome the five C's of why most people don't have a computer in the living room: cost, consumption of electric power, cooling noise, case style, and complexity of operation. (I wrote <a href="https://pineight.com/mw/?title=HTPCs_are_for_geeks" class="postlink">more details about it elsewhere</a>.) I'd love to be able to recommend a make and model of computer to someone as an alternative to consoles, so long as it overcomes these five C's.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>lidnariq</b> [ Thu Jun 26, 2014 1:45 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Low-cost living room emulation machine</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />It's going to be really hard to compete with the RasPi's very low cost and comparatively low power consumption, and people have already written emulator frontends for it. A case and the controllers are the only remaining question.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Movax12</b> [ Thu Jun 26, 2014 5:25 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Low-cost living room emulation machine</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Cheapest thing that is decent is probably an original xbox. A used xbox shouldn't cost more than ~$30. It can output component video, the emulator UI's are designed for the living room, and most have an option for at least 720p video. It runs ports of popular PC emulators. It also has a controller that works well with most systems. CONS: The component video pack might cost you a bit more, and you are going to have to learn how to mod it, or find someone to mod it for you.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


